{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17490982","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17490982"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:32+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T05:26:32+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"792"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/792"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.01,0.22,0.59,0.02,0.16]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103751"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"792","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/792"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"792"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86173"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"37"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1120"},{"type":"tags","id":"1487"},{"type":"tags","id":"4097"},{"type":"tags","id":"4824"},{"type":"tags","id":"4970"},{"type":"tags","id":"4983"},{"type":"tags","id":"6400"},{"type":"tags","id":"6442"},{"type":"tags","id":"9663"},{"type":"tags","id":"11643"},{"type":"tags","id":"11644"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"1385"},{"type":"contributions","id":"1497"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"44334"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103751","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/103751"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 28-year-old man presents to the General Practice clinic with a two-day history of gradually worsening right-sided scrotal pain and dysuria. He has a medical history of bilateral orchidopexy in childhood for undescended testes and appendicectomy at age 17. He takes no regular medications. He reports starting a new sexual relationship with a female partner.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. The right epididymis is swollen and tender. The right testis is soft and smooth, measuring 3 cm in length. Elevation of the right testicle alleviates the pain. The left hemiscrotum is normal on examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Tumour marker studies","Doppler ultrasound","First pass urine NAAT","Fine needle aspiration cytology","Midstream urine microscopy and culture"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with features typical of epididymitis, including gradual onset scrotal pain, dysuria, and a tender epididymis. In sexually active men aged 14-35 years, epididymitis is most commonly caused by \u003Cem\u003EChlamydia trachomatis\u003C/em\u003E or \u003Cem\u003ENeisseria gonorrhoeae\u003C/em\u003E. An important cause of scrotal pain to not miss is testicular torsion. The gradual onset, presence of Prehn\u0027s sign (pain relief on testicular elevation), and history of orchidopexy make torsion unlikely. If testicular torsion was suspected as the likely diagnosis, immediate surgical investigation is indicated.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFirst pass urine NAAT\u003C/strong\u003E (nucleic acid amplification test) is the gold standard investigation for diagnosing these sexually transmitted infections. It is highly sensitive and specific for detecting both chlamydia and gonorrhoea.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMidstream urine microscopy and culture\u003C/strong\u003E would be appropriate if investigating a urinary tract infection, but this is an uncommon cause of epididymitis in young men. The presence of a new sexual partner makes a sexually transmitted infection more likely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDoppler ultrasound\u003C/strong\u003E would be the investigation of choice if the diagnosis was uncertain. Scrotal ultrasound with Doppler can effectively differentiate between various causes of scrotal pain by assessing blood flow patterns. In epididymitis, increased blood flow to the epididymis is typically seen. In testicular torsion, there is decreased or absent blood flow to the affected testis. Ultrasound can also identify other causes of scrotal pain such as testicular tumours (appearing as hypoechoic or heterogeneous masses), hydrocele (anechoic fluid collection around the testis), varicocele (dilated veins in the pampiniform plexus), or abscess formation (complex fluid collections). However, in this case, the clinical presentation strongly suggests epididymitis of sexually transmitted origin, making first pass urine NAAT the more appropriate initial investigation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETumour marker studies\u003C/strong\u003E would be indicated if a testicular tumour was suspected. However, the acute presentation, normal testicular examination, and tender epididymis make this diagnosis unlikely.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFine needle aspiration cytology\u003C/strong\u003E is contraindicated in scrotal masses as it may spread tumour cells if a malignancy is present and risks damage to the testis or epididymis.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Epididymitis in sexually active men aged 14-35 years is most commonly caused by Chlamydia trachomatis or Neisseria gonorrhoeae.","First pass urine NAAT is the gold standard test for diagnosing chlamydia and gonorrhoea.","Prehn\u0027s sign (pain relief on testicular elevation) helps differentiate epididymitis from testicular torsion."],"references":["McConaghy JR, Panchal B. Epididymitis: An Overview. Am Fam Physician. 2016 Nov 1;94(9):723-726. PMID: 27929243.","Australian STI Guidelines Contributors, 2018. Chlamydia. Australian Sexual Health Alliance (ASHA). Access at: http://www.sti.guidelines.org.au/sexually-transmissible-infections/chlamydia?highlight=WyJjaGxhbXlkaWEiXQ==#diagnosis.","Srinath H. Acute scrotal pain. Aust Fam Physician. 2013 Nov;42(11):790\u20133."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86173"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"792"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"86173","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/86173"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-05-26T15:07:52+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-26T15:10:40+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"792"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"103751"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"14","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/14"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udda0","name":"Infectious Diseases","synonyms":["ID"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2021-05-21T07:51:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdA